[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(18) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Whatsoever ye shall bind on earth.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—(See Note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 16:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) The promise before made to Peter is now extended not only to the other Apostles, but to the whole society of which they were the representatives, and is, of course, to be understood as dependent on the same implied, though not expressed, condition. So far as the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ecclesia",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was true to its Lord, and guided by His Spirit, it was not to think that its decisions depended on any temporal power. They were clothed, as truth and righteousness are ever clothed, with a divine authority. As connected with the treatment of individual offenders, the words “bind” and “loose” may seem here to approximate more closely than in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 16:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to “condemning” and “absolving” in their force, but there is no ground for setting aside, even here, their received meaning in the language of the scribes. The Christian had to apply general laws to particular instances. The trial of each offender became a ruling case. It was binding or loosing, directly as interpreting the Law, only secondarily and indirectly as punishing or pardoning.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
